Spanish Housing Prices Rise 9.3% to a New Record High: Signs of a Stressed Market

This article is for informational purposes only and does not constitute investment advice or a recommendation in any form.

Spain’s residential market has reached new historical highs. According to the II Solvia Market View 2025, the average housing price climbed to €2,251 per square meter in the second quarter of 2025, marking a 9.3% year-on-year increase. The rise underscores the sector’s resilience despite slower economic growth and previously tighter monetary conditions.

Figures from the Ministry of Housing, Mobility and Urban Agenda (MITMA) confirm a similar trend, reporting the average price of free-market housing at €2,093.5 per square meter, up 6.2% from a year earlier. Though the methodologies differ, both data sets reflect the same reality: Spanish property prices are still rising faster than household incomes, defying predictions of a post-rate-hike slowdown.

The surge is being fuelled by three structural forces — limited supply, rising construction costs, and sustained domestic and foreign demand. Construction costs have jumped 27.5% since 2020, according to UVE Valoraciones, driven by higher energy and material prices. Meanwhile, annual housing completions remain well below what the market needs: Spain builds between 80,000 and 90,000 homes a year, while the Bank of Spain estimates around 250,000 units are required annually to balance supply and demand.

The imbalance is most visible in large urban and coastal markets. Data from Idealista show that by October 2025, prices reached €4,150 per square meter in Madrid and €4,350 per square meter in Barcelona. In Málaga, average prices rose more than 12% year-on-year, to about €3,250 per square meter, supported by robust foreign investment and the scarcity of developable land.

The rental market tells a similar story. Idealista reported that average rents hit €13.3 per square meter nationally in October 2025, a 10.2% annual increase, setting a new all-time high. In cities like Valencia, Seville, and Bilbao, the number of available rental listings has fallen more than 20% over the past year, intensifying competition among tenants and pushing rents further upward.

Despite these pressures, investment activity remains strong. According to CBRE’s Real Estate Market Outlook 2025, real-estate investment in Spain totalled €12.9 billion in the first nine months of 2025, up 44% year-on-year, making it the third-highest volume on record. Activity is being driven by the build-to-rent and logistics segments, as well as renewed institutional appetite for prime residential assets.

Foreign buyers also continue to play an outsized role. The Spanish Land Registrars Association’s 2024 Yearbook reported that non-residents accounted for 14.6% of all home purchases, led by buyers from the United Kingdom, Germany, and France. This cross-border demand has helped sustain prices in tourism-oriented regions such as the Balearic Islands, the Canary Islands, the Costa del Sol, and Valencia.

Nevertheless, analysts caution that the current pace of growth may not be sustainable. Access to homeownership is increasingly difficult for middle-income households, and the share of families spending more than 30% of their income on housing continues to rise. The Bank of Spain has noted that while there are no signs of widespread overvaluation, the gap between incomes and prices has widened to levels similar to those seen in 2010. Structural reforms in land policy and public housing supply, it warns, will be crucial to restoring balance.

Against this backdrop, alternative financing models are gaining momentum. Real-estate crowdfunding is emerging as a tool to channel private savings into specific development or renovation projects, lowering entry barriers and improving transparency. According to the European Crowdfunding Network, real-estate investment through collective platforms has grown at an average annual rate of more than 25% in Europe since 2018, with Spain among the most dynamic emerging markets.

